The Telegraph - Calcutta : Nation

NATION BRIEFS

 Mumbai, March 12 (PTI): A case was registered today against Maharashtra Navnirman Sena chief Raj Thackeray for his reported comments against north Indians at a recent party meeting. 

 The case relates to Thackeray promoting enmity among people on the basis of birth of place and language, additional commissioner of police (west region) Bipin Bihari said.

 New Delhi (PTI): Barring the Indian Institute of Management at Lucknow, the rest of the IIMs are facing shortage of faculty, HRD minister Arjun Singh said in a written reply in the Rajya Sabha today. Some IIMs have raised their intake in fellowship programmes to increase the number of persons eligible to take up faculty positions, he added. 

 Chennai (PTI): Carnatic vocalist T. Muktha died on Sunday after a brief illness. She was 92. Muktha was instrumental in popularising the works of Muthuswamy Dikshitar, a Carnatic music composer, and has received many awards, including the Sangeet Natak Akademi Award. She is survived by a daughter. 

 Muzaffarnagar (PTI):A bride here rejected her would-be husband when she found he was physically challenged, police said on Monday. Rita refused to marry Rakesh when she noticed his amputated arm during the varmala (garland exchange) ceremony. The grooms relatives were beaten up for hiding the disability.

 Tamil in HC

 Chennai (PTI): The Centre will reconsider the Tamil Nadu governments proposal to introduce Tamil as an official language in Madras High Court, Union law minister H.R. Bhardwaj said in a letter to chief minister M. Karunanidhi.

 Thiruvananthapuram (PTI): A total of 607 policemen in Kerala are involved in criminal cases, state home minister Kodiyeri Balakrishnan said on Monday. The list of those facing criminal charges include 85 from the law and order wing, he said.




